The     story that is emerging about the collapse of Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=
=80=99s crypto exchange, FTX, and its affiliated trading firm, Alameda Rese=
arch, is that FTX took customer money for crypto trades, and Alameda used i=
ts own money for crypto trades, and nobody=C2=A0kept track of the money, so=
 Alameda kept using FTX customer money for trades, and FTX didn=E2=80=99t n=
otice, and Alameda kept losing that money, and it also didn=E2=80=99t notic=
e? And then one day someone noticed and the whole thing vanished in a puff =
of smoke? I don=E2=80=99t know! That story makes no sense to me at all! And=
 I don=E2=80=99t think that it is a=C2=A0good=C2=A0story or anything; in ma=
ny ways an orderly fraud would be better than a vast money-sucking whirlwin=
d of chaos. But =E2=80=9Cnobody kept track of the money=E2=80=9D does seem =
to be the story that everyone is going with.
Here is a Wall Street Journal story about  the early days of Alameda:

Mr. Bankman-Fried placed huge bets on crypto assets but paid little heed to=
 the risk of those bets, brushing off the staffers=E2=80=99 concerns, accor=
ding to people familiar with the matter. The firm commingled trading capita=
l with operating cash and had poor record-keeping that left its profits and=
 losses unclear, they said.
=E2=80=9CHe didn=E2=80=99t want to feel constrained,=E2=80=9D said Naia Bou=
scal, a former software engineer at Alameda who left with [Alameda co-found=
er Tara] Mac Aulay and the others. =E2=80=9CBut as a result we ended up not=
 really knowing how much money we even had.=E2=80=9D

They left in 2018. =E2=80=9CMr. Bankman-Fried told The Wall Street Journal =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0that Alameda addressed the accounting, risk and other issues=
 they raised,=E2=80=9D which makes it sound like Alameda=C2=A0did=C2=A0know=
 how much money it had for the last four years, but in fact Bankman-Fried h=
as been saying  on Twitter and  in interviews that Alameda and FTX did=C2=
=A0not=C2=A0keep particularly careful track of their money, so who knows. T=
he Journal goes on:

Mr. Bankman-Fried had worked at quantitative trading giant Jane Street Capi=
tal LLC, a firm that has extensive risk controls. But when colleagues at Al=
ameda proposed setting up rigorous structures and systems for risk, complia=
nce and accounting, Mr. Bankman-Fried was dismissive of the idea, according=
 to the people.
He said such extensive controls could crimp Alameda=E2=80=99s activity and =
limit how fast the firm could move to place trades, the people said, reduci=
ng potential profit.
Alameda built a trading algorithm to make a large number of automated, rapi=
d-fire trades, but some at the firm feared it couldn=E2=80=99t keep track o=
f all the activity, the people said. The staffers said Alameda needed to do=
 a better job tracking its trading to properly account for its gains and lo=
sses, but Mr. Bankman-Fried rejected the idea, according to the people.

One thing about   working at Jane Street is that, when you show up for work=
 at Jane Street as a trader, your job is not, like, =E2=80=9Crebuild Jane S=
treet using only materials found in nature.=E2=80=9D Your job at Jane Stree=
t is more like =E2=80=9Cwe have built a good technology stack and risk-mana=
gement and accounting and performance attribution systems, now go find some=
 profitable trades.=E2=80=9D You find some trades that you think are profit=
able, you do them, and if you=E2=80=99re right then Jane Street=E2=80=99s e=
xisting systems will notice and reward you. If you=E2=80=99re wrong, the ri=
sk systems will stop you. You are just in charge of finding the good trades=
.
If, later, you leave to start your own firm, you will take with you your sk=
ill at finding good trades. (Which seems like a perishable thing.) But it=
=E2=80=99s not obvious that you will take with you Jane Street=E2=80=99s ri=
sk-management culture, and you certainly won=E2=80=99t take its risk-manage=
ment=C2=A0systems. And then when your colleagues say to you =E2=80=9Chey, l=
et=E2=80=99s set up some risk systems and hire an accountant, like we had a=
t Jane Street,=E2=80=9D you can reply =E2=80=9Cnah, I=E2=80=99d prefer to i=
gnore that stuff, like I did at Jane Street.=E2=80=9D You=E2=80=99re both r=
ight! Someone else at Jane Street set up those systems so you didn=E2=80=99=
t have to worry about them. But now you=E2=80=99re in charge, and if you do=
n=E2=80=99t worry about them no one will, and then you end up not knowing h=
ow much money you have, or how much you=E2=80=99re making or losing, or how=
 much you owe your customers.
Meanwhile here is a Financial Times story about  the lavish later days of F=
TX:

A lack of internal controls that are typical of large financial companies m=
eant FTX=E2=80=99s spending went largely unchecked, according to former emp=
loyees and filings in the group=E2=80=99s Delaware bankruptcy case.
=E2=80=9C[It was] kids leading kids,=E2=80=9D said one former employee. =E2=
=80=9CThe entire operation was idiotically inefficient, but equally mesmeri=
sing,=E2=80=9D they added. =E2=80=9CI had never witnessed so much money in =
my life. I don=E2=80=99t think anybody had, including SBF.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=A6
The perks enjoyed by employees of the now-collapsed exchange included round=
-the-clock catering in the Bahamas office, =E2=80=9Cin addition to the free=
 groceries, barbershop pop-up, and bi-weekly massages=E2=80=9D, according t=
o one employee.
FTX also provided Bahamas staff with a =E2=80=9Cfull suite of cars and gas =
covered for all employees [and] unlimited, full expense covered trips to an=
y office globally=E2=80=9D, the employee added. Staff at FTX US, its separa=
te arm for the American market, were allowed $200 a day in DoorDash food de=
livery credits.
Alameda Research, a crypto hedge fund founded by Bankman-Fried, also owes $=
55,319 to the Margaritaville Beach Resort in Nassau, which was founded by U=
S musician Jimmy Buffett, according to bankruptcy filings this week. A =E2=
=80=9CWho=E2=80=99s To Blame=E2=80=9D margarita at one of the resort=E2=80=
=99s bars costs $13.

I think that this is best understood as an accounting problem. A month ago,=
  a common perception of FTX was that it had =E2=80=9Cone of the highest re=
venue/profit/valuation per employee as any company in the world.=E2=80=9D A=
s far as I can tell,=C2=A0FTX=C2=A0believed this. If in fact your employees=
 are incredibly good at making money, then lavishing them with perks is sim=
ply optimal. Allowing $200 a day in DoorDash to prevent your insanely profi=
table employees from ever having to think about their meal budget is a good=
 business move. Your employees=E2=80=99 time and attention is so valuable t=
hat it is foolish to make them waste time filling out expense reports.
But a big part of the reason that FTX believed it was so profitable is that=
 nobody made any effort to keep track of the money. If you lose $4 billion =
trading and borrow $8 billion of customer money to cover the gap and=C2=A0d=
on=E2=80=99t keep track of that borrowing, then it looks like you made $4 b=
illion trading, and you will say things like =E2=80=9Cwe are incredibly pro=
fitable per employee, $200 DoorDash for everyone!=E2=80=9D FTX spent like t=
he company it thought it was, but it didn=E2=80=99t bother to find out what=
 kind of company it actually was.

