<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A fact about financial markets that occasional=
ly produces strange results is that the total market value of a thing is, c=
onventionally, (1) the amount of that thing that exists times (2) the price=
 of the last trade. So Bloomberg tells me that there are about 304.5 millio=
n shares of GameStop Corp. stock outstanding, and they closed at $25.60 yes=
terday, so GameStop=E2=80=99s market capitalization =E2=80=94=C2=A0the tota=
l value of its stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0is 304.5 million times $25.60, or about=
 $8 billion. Nobody recently bought or sold all of GameStop for $8 billion,=
 and if somebody did, the price would probably not be $8 billion.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> But if you wanted to buy or sell=C2=A0<em>one=C2=A0</em>share of GameS=
top, the price you=E2=80=99d pay or get would be about $25.60, and you can =
multiply.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One type of strange result you can get from th=
is is that if you have some weird small stock or cryptocurrency that doesn=
=E2=80=99t trade very much, you can give it a very large market capitalizat=
ion=C2=A0by selling one share or token to your buddy at an inflated price, =
and then you can go around telling people =E2=80=9Cooh look at the huge mar=
ket cap of this thing, it is so valuable, it must have discovered a cure fo=
r cancer,=E2=80=9D and maybe you can do bad stuff with that. We have talked=
 about the infamous New Jersey deli that was <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/29848628.258549/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNv=
