<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">FTX</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/29848628.258549/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTcvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1mdHgtd2FzLW5=
vdC12ZXJ5LWNhcmVmdWw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEzMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbW=
FpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTMwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb=
25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe4970526" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">    story that is em=
erging</a> about the collapse of Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s crypto exchang=
e, FTX, and its affiliated trading firm, Alameda Research, is that FTX took=
 customer money for crypto trades, and Alameda used its own money for crypt=
o trades, and nobody=C2=A0<em>kept track of the money</em>, so Alameda kept=
 using FTX customer money for trades, and FTX didn=E2=80=99t notice, and Al=
ameda kept losing that money, and it also didn=E2=80=99t notice? And then o=
ne day someone noticed and the whole thing vanished in a puff of smoke? I d=
on=E2=80=99t know! That story makes no sense to me at all! And I don=E2=80=
=99t think that it is a=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>story or anything; in many =
ways an orderly fraud would be better than a vast money-sucking whirlwind o=
f chaos. But =E2=80=9Cnobody kept track of the money=E2=80=9D does seem to =
be the story that everyone is going with.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a Wall Street Journal story about <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29848628.258549/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9lYXJseS1hbGFtZWRhLXN0YWZmZXJzLXF1aXQtYWZ0Z=
XItYmF0dGxpbmctc2FtLWJhbmttYW4tZnJpZWQtb3Zlci1yaXNrLWNvbXBsaWFuY2UtY29uY2Vy=
bnMtMTE2Njk4MTA3MjM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB232a9eb1" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the early d=
ays of Alameda</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Bankman-Fried placed huge bets on crypto a=
ssets but paid little heed to the risk of those bets, brushing off the staf=
fers=E2=80=99 concerns, according to people familiar with the matter. The f=
irm commingled trading capital with operating cash and had poor record-keep=
ing that left its profits and losses unclear, they said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CHe didn=E2=80=99t want to feel constr=
ained,=E2=80=9D said Naia Bouscal, a former software engineer at Alameda wh=
o left with [Alameda co-founder Tara] Mac Aulay and the others. =E2=80=9CBu=
t as a result we ended up not really knowing how much money we even had.=E2=
=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They left in 2018. =E2=80=9CMr. Bankman-Fried =
told The Wall Street Journal =E2=80=A6=C2=A0that Alameda addressed the acco=
unting, risk and other issues they raised,=E2=80=9D which makes it sound li=
ke Alameda=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>know how much money it had for the last f=
our years, but in fact Bankman-Fried has been saying <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29848628.258549/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNv=
bS9TQkZfRlRYL3N0YXR1cy8xNTkwNzA5MTcyOTM2Nzk4MjA4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9=
e336ee1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> on Twitter</a> and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/29848628.258549/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudm94LmNvbS9mdXR1cmUtcGVy=
ZmVjdC8yMzQ2MjMzMy9zYW0tYmFua21hbi1mcmllZC1mdHgtY3J5cHRvY3VycmVuY3ktZWZmZWN=
0aXZlLWFsdHJ1aXNtLWNyeXB0by1iYWhhbWFzLXBoaWxhbnRocm9weQ/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBf4aeea86" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> in interviews</a> that Alameda and FTX did=C2=A0<e=
m>not=C2=A0</em>keep particularly careful track of their money, so who know=
s. The Journal goes on:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Bankman-Fried had worked at quantitative t=
rading giant Jane Street Capital LLC, a firm that has extensive risk contro=
ls. But when colleagues at Alameda proposed setting up rigorous structures =
and systems for risk, compliance and accounting, Mr. Bankman-Fried was dism=
issive of the idea, according to the people.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He said such extensive controls could crimp Al=
ameda=E2=80=99s activity and limit how fast the firm could move to place tr=
ades, the people said, reducing potential profit.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alameda built a trading algorithm to make a la=
rge number of automated, rapid-fire trades, but some at the firm feared it =
couldn=E2=80=99t keep track of all the activity, the people said. The staff=
ers said Alameda needed to do a better job tracking its trading to properly=
 account for its gains and losses, but Mr. Bankman-Fried rejected the idea,=
 according to the people.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing about <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/29848628.258549/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNv=
bS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMjMvZnR4LWZsaXBwZWQtamFuZS1zdHJlZXQtcy1yaXN=
rLW9ic2Vzc2lvbi1kaXNhc3Rlci1mb2xsb3dlZC1mb3ItYmFua21hbi1mcmllZD9jbXBpZD1CQk=
QxMTMwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlc=
iZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjExMzAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cBae6d6836" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">  working at Jane Street</a> is that, when you show =
up for work at Jane Street as a trader, your job is not, like, =E2=80=9Creb=
uild Jane Street using only materials found in nature.=E2=80=9D Your job at=
 Jane Street is more like =E2=80=9Cwe have built a good technology stack an=
d risk-management and accounting and performance attribution systems, now g=
o find some profitable trades.=E2=80=9D You find some trades that you think=
 are profitable, you do them, and if you=E2=80=99re right then Jane Street=
=E2=80=99s existing systems will notice and reward you. If you=E2=80=99re w=
rong, the risk systems will stop you. You are just in charge of finding the=
 good trades.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If, later, you leave to start your own firm, y=
ou will take with you your skill at finding good trades. (Which seems like =
a perishable thing.) But it=E2=80=99s not obvious that you will take with y=
ou Jane Street=E2=80=99s risk-management culture, and you certainly won=E2=
=80=99t take its risk-management=C2=A0<em>systems</em>. And then when your =
colleagues say to you =E2=80=9Chey, let=E2=80=99s set up some risk systems =
and hire an accountant, like we had at Jane Street,=E2=80=9D you can reply =
=E2=80=9Cnah, I=E2=80=99d prefer to ignore that stuff, like I did at Jane S=
treet.=E2=80=9D You=E2=80=99re both right! Someone else at Jane Street set =
up those systems so you didn=E2=80=99t have to worry about them. But now yo=
u=E2=80=99re in charge, and if you don=E2=80=99t worry about them no one wi=
ll, and then you end up not knowing how much money you have, or how much yo=
u=E2=80=99re making or losing, or how much you owe your customers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile here is a Financial Times story abou=
t <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29848628.258549/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvN2NmYmI4OTQtYTMzMi00NjI5LWE0MTctNGJjZGE=
yN2ViNmU3/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfde312a3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the lavish later days=
 of FTX</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A lack of internal controls that are typical o=
f large financial companies meant FTX=E2=80=99s spending went largely unche=
cked, according to former employees and filings in the group=E2=80=99s Dela=
ware bankruptcy case.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9C[It was] kids leading kids,=E2=80=9D =
said one former employee. =E2=80=9CThe entire operation was idiotically ine=
fficient, but equally mesmerising,=E2=80=9D they added. =E2=80=9CI had neve=
r witnessed so much money in my life. I don=E2=80=99t think anybody had, in=
cluding SBF.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The perks enjoyed by employees of the now-coll=
apsed exchange included round-the-clock catering in the Bahamas office, =E2=
=80=9Cin addition to the free groceries, barbershop pop-up, and bi-weekly m=
assages=E2=80=9D, according to one employee.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">FTX also provided Bahamas staff with a =E2=80=
=9Cfull suite of cars and gas covered for all employees [and] unlimited, fu=
ll expense covered trips to any office globally=E2=80=9D, the employee adde=
d. Staff at FTX US, its separate arm for the American market, were allowed =
$200 a day in DoorDash food delivery credits.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alameda Research, a crypto hedge fund founded =
by Bankman-Fried, also owes $55,319 to the Margaritaville Beach Resort in N=
assau, which was founded by US musician Jimmy Buffett, according to bankrup=
tcy filings this week. A =E2=80=9CWho=E2=80=99s To Blame=E2=80=9D margarita=
 at one of the resort=E2=80=99s bars costs $13.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think that this is best understood as an acc=
ounting problem. A month ago, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/29848628.258549/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9XdUJsb2NrY2hhaW4vc3R=
hdHVzLzE1ODk3ODI3MzI0NDM2MzU3MTI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6ad783bc" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> a common perception of FTX</a> was that it had =E2=80=9Cone of the highes=
t revenue/profit/valuation per employee as any company in the world.=E2=80=
=9D As far as I can tell,=C2=A0<em>FTX=C2=A0</em>believed this. If in fact =
your employees are incredibly good at making money, then lavishing them wit=
h perks is simply optimal. Allowing $200 a day in DoorDash to prevent your =
insanely profitable employees from ever having to think about their meal bu=
dget is a good business move. Your employees=E2=80=99 time and attention is=
 so valuable that it is foolish to make them waste time filling out expense=
 reports.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But a big part of the reason that FTX believed=
 it was so profitable is that <em>nobody made any effort to keep track of t=
he money</em>. If you lose $4 billion trading and borrow $8 billion of cust=
omer money to cover the gap and=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t keep track of that b=
orrowing</em>, then it looks like you made $4 billion trading, and you will=
 say things like =E2=80=9Cwe are incredibly profitable per employee, $200 D=
oorDash for everyone!=E2=80=9D FTX spent like the company it thought it was=
, but it didn=E2=80=99t bother to find out what kind of company it actually=
 was.</p>
